[[File:44, Lëtzebuergerstrooss, Esch-101.jpg|thumb|A mosque in Luxembourg]]

'''[[Muslim]]s in [[Luxembourg]]''' are a super-minority together with: [[Protestantism|Protestants]], [[Orthodox Church|Orthodox Christians]], and [[Judaism|Jews]].  Since 2015, [[Islam]] is legally recognized in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sandzakpress.net/finally-good-news-from-europe-islam-recognized-in-luxembourg |title=Finally good news from Europe, Islam recognized in Luxembourg}}</ref>

== Migration ==
Up until the 1970s, Luxembourg's Muslim population was small.  In the mid-1970s, the Muslim population consisted of around 300 people, rising to over 3,000 by the mid-1990s.  Since then, the population has doubled due to asylum-seekers from former [[Yugoslavia]], mostly [[Bosniaks]]. The refugees came in waves and, aside from the Bosniaks, these were constituted by Muslims from [[Albania]], [[Kosovo]], [[Serbia]], and [[Montenegro]]. Most asylum seekers were initially expected to stay less than a few years.<ref>{{cite web|title=Anti-Islamic reactions in the EU: Luxemburg|url=http://fra.europa.eu/fraWebsite/attachments/Luxemburg.pdf|publisher=European Monitoring Centre on Racism and Xenophobia|accessdate=22 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Immigration in Luxembourg: New Challenges for an Old Country|url=http://www.migrationinformation.org/Profiles/display.cfm?ID=587|publisher=Migration Information Source|accessdate=22 August 2012}}</ref> Aside from the refugees, the Muslim population was also increased by workers who migrated after the labour agreement between Luxembourg and Yugoslavia.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=Yearbook of Muslims in Europe, Volume 7|last=Scharbrodt|first=Oliver|last2=Akgonul|first2=Samim|last3=Alibašić|first3=Ahmet|last4=Nielsen|first4=Jorgen|last5=Racius|first5=Egdunas|publisher=BRILL|year=2015|isbn=9789004298897|location=Leiden|pages=378}}</ref> By 2013, Muslims in Luxembourg were constituted of Bosnians (2,303), Moroccans (616), Albanians (502), Turks (487), Tunisians (374), Algerians (331), and Iranians (322).<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|title=Yearbook of Muslims in Europe, Volume 6|last=Nielsen|first=Jorgen|last2=Akgonul|first2=Samim|last3=Alibašić|first3=Ahmet|last4=Racius|first4=Egdunas|publisher=BRILL|year=2014|isbn=9789004277540|location=Leiden|pages=388}}</ref> 

== Population ==
The bulk of the Muslim population lives in urban areas with 70 percent residing in Luxembourg and four other [[List of towns in Luxembourg|cities]].<ref name=":1" /> According to the Assembly of the Muslim Community in Luxembourg, it is estimated that about 10,000 to 15,000 Muslims presently reside in the Grand-Duchy.<ref>Assemblée de la Communauté Musulmane du Grand-Duché de Luxembourg - [http://www.shoura.lu/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Rapport-dactivite%CC%81s-de-la-Shoura-2012-2013-Rapport-du-pre%CC%81sident.pdf Rapport d'activités de la shoura pour l'année 2012/2013], page 4</ref> However, it has been illegal for the government to collect statistics on religious beliefs and practices.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legilux.public.lu/leg/a/archives/1979/0291104/0291104.pdf#page=2|title=Mémorial A, 1979, No. 29|publisher=Service central de législation|language=fr|format=PDF|accessdate=6 August 2017}}</ref> Furthermore, it is unclear how many are citizens of the Grand-Duchy.

There are currently six mosques in Luxembourg:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shoura.lu/?page_id=542 |title=Assemblée de la Communauté Musulmane du Grand-Duché de Luxembourg}}</ref> [[Mamer]] (which is also home to the Islamic Cultural Centre), Esch-sur-Alzette, Wiltz, Diekirch and Luxembourg City. About 1,000 adults attend Friday prayers regularly in these places of worship.<ref name=":1" /> There is also an increasing number of converts and this is reflected in the sermons in the mosques, which are delivered in [[Arabic]], [[Serbo-Croatian]], [[French language|French]], and [[English language|English]].<ref name=":0" /> 

