[[File:Rabha man.jpg|thumb|A Rabha gentleman, in front of his house in a forest village, Gayarkata, Jalpaiguri]] '''Rabha''' (also '''Rava''') is an [[Assamese people|indigenous Assamese]] community of the Indian states of [[Assam]], [[Meghalaya]] and [[West Bengal]]. The language/dialect spoken by the Rabha people is mostly [[Assamese language|Assamese]] but in some areas the [[Rabha language|Rabha]] dialect is also spoken. In [[Assam]], the Rabhas live mostly in [[Goalpara]] and [[Kamrup Rural district|Kamrup]] districts. In [[Meghalaya]], Rabhas are mostly found in Garo Hills districts. In [[West Bengal]], Rabha people mainly live in [[Jalpaiguri district]] and [[Cooch Behar district]]. Moreover, almost, 70 per cent of them live in [[Jalpaiguri district]]. The whole area of Eastern and Western [[Dooars]], may be termed as the cradle land of the Rabhas. The Rabhas refer to themselves as Koch and assert a connection to the historical [[Koch Kingdom]].
==Ethnicity and language==
The Rabhas belong to the [[Indo Mongoloid]] group of people and have similarities with other members of [[Koch people|Koch]] group such as [[Garo (tribe)|Garos]], [[Koch-Kachari|Kachari]], [[Mech tribe|Mech]], [[Koch Rajbongshi people|Koch]], [[Hajong people|Hajong]] and others.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mitra|1953|p=cxxxviii}}</ref> Most of the Rabhas of Dooars refer to themselves as Rabha, but some of them often declare themselves as ''Kocha''.<ref>{{Harvnb|Karlsson|2000|pp=55–8}}</ref>{{clarify|reason=we seem to have lost the cite details|date=July 2017}}
[[File:Crafts Museum New Delhi 3 Sep 2010-14.JPG|thumb|left|A traditional Rabha house]]
==Religion and culture== [[File:Rabha girls dance with arms.jpg|thumb|Rabha girls are dancing in their traditional costumes in a forest village in West Bengal]] {{bar box |title=Religion among Rabha, 2001<ref name="census2001">{{citation| title = Census of India - Socio-cultural aspects, Table ST-14|year=2001| publisher = Government of India, Ministry of Home Affairs}}</ref> |titlebar=#Fcd116 |left1=Religion |right1=Percent |float=left |bars= {{bar percent|[[Hinduism]]|#FF6600|98.83}} {{bar percent|[[Christianity]]|#9955BB|0.62}} {{bar percent|Others|#808080|0.56}} }} Rabha people traditionally practice a few [[Animism|animistic]] rituals. However, today they more often follow a faith, which is a blend of some [[Hinduism|Hindu]] and a few animistic rituals. There are considerable differences in ritual practices among forest Rabhas who still live in the forest villages and the Rabhas that live in the villages as cultivators. The forest Rabhas follow traditional animistic practices tinged with some rituals of mainstream Hinduism. On the other hand, village Rabhas have merged with local Hindus as far as their religious practices are concerned.<ref>{{Harvnb|Das & Raha|1967|p=130}}</ref>{{clarify|reason=we seem to have lost the cite details|date=July 2017}}
Rabha people's religious world is pervaded with various spirits and natural objects. The main deity of the Rabhas is called ''Rishi''. ''Rishi'', for the forest Rabhas as well as village Rabhas, is a male deity. He is also known as ''Mahakal''. Forest Rabhas worship him in all important social and religious ceremonies.<ref>{{Harvnb|Karlsson|2000|p=162}}</ref>{{clarify|reason=we seem to have lost the cite details|date=July 2017}}
